# EZRA Governance Rules for Cursor Agent
# Copy this file to your project root as .cursorrules
# Customize the rules below for your project

## Standards
- Follow the coding standards defined in .ezra/settings.yaml
- Use consistent naming conventions as specified in the standards section
- Maximum file complexity must not exceed the configured threshold
- All new code must include appropriate error handling

## Security
- Never hardcode secrets, API keys, passwords, or tokens
- Always validate user input before processing
- Use parameterized queries for database operations
- Check .ezra/settings.yaml security section for project-specific rules

## Before Making Changes
- Read .ezra/governance.yaml to understand project phase and constraints
- Check .ezra/settings.yaml oversight.level for current enforcement mode
- If oversight level is "strict" or "gate", verify changes against all rules before proceeding
- Check .ezra/memory/red-lines.yaml — never violate any listed red line

## After Making Changes
- Run health check: `npx ezra-claude-code scan` (or `ezra scan` if globally installed)
- If health score drops below the threshold in .ezra/settings.yaml, fix issues before committing
- Record any architectural decisions in .ezra/decisions/ using YAML format
- Update .ezra/memory/key-facts.yaml if new critical project facts emerge

## Decision Tracking
- When making architectural choices, create a decision file:
  - File: .ezra/decisions/AD-NNN.yaml
  - Format: category, decision, rationale, status: locked, date
- Categories: AD (Architecture), BD (Business), TC (Technical), SR (Scope), SC (Security), DD (Data)

## Testing
- All new features must have tests
- Run existing test suite before committing — zero regressions allowed
- Minimum coverage target is defined in .ezra/settings.yaml standards section

## Documentation
- Update relevant documentation when changing public APIs
- Keep README.md current with new features
- Add JSDoc/TSDoc comments to exported functions
